  <h3>Information:</h3>
  <p>The Illumina Infinium Methylation platforms relies on two key processes. The first one is the bisulfite conversion, and the second one is the use of specific labeled antibodies.
    Here is a brief explanation on the steps of the Infinium protocol:
  </p>
  <br>
  <ul class="list-group">
    <li class="list-group-item">
      <strong>Bisulfite conversion</strong>: We convert 500 ng of high quality DNA (no fragmented, not contaminated with proteins, RNA, phenol,â€¦). In this step methylated
      			 cytosines will remain unchanged, while not methylted cytosines will convert into uracils.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <center><img src="bisulfiteconversion.png"></center><br>
  <center><img  src="bisulfiteconversion_2.png"></center>
	<ul class="list-group">
    <li class="list-group-item">
			<strong>Amplification</strong>: Using random primers along with an engineer modified Phi29 DNA polymerase, we are amplifying the original DNA over 100 times, without introducing
  						the bias that a PCR would introduce. Note that in this step, uracils coming from unmethylated cytosines will be amplified as thymines.
		</li>
  </ul>
  <center><img src="amplification.png"></center><br>
	<ul class="list-group">
    <li class="list-group-item">
			<strong>Fragmentation</strong>: In order to hybridize properly the DNA into the array, the bisulfit converted DNA is fragmented in a size ranging from 300nt to 500nt.
		</li>
  </ul>
  <br>
	<ul class="list-group">
    <li class="list-group-item">
			  <strong>Hibridization</strong>: Fragmented bisulfite DNA is hybridized on the HumanMenthylation450 bead chip, allowing specific hybridization to occur based on homology to a 50 nucleotide
      				  sequence present in the beads. Unhybridized and non-specifically hybridized DNA are washed away by using properly formulated buffers.
    </li>
  </ul>
	<center><img src="hybridization.png"></center><br>
  <ul class="list-group">
    <li class="list-group-item">
			<strong>Single Base Extension</strong>: All 4 dideoxynucleotides are incorporated. ddCTP and ddGTP are labeled with biotin, while ddTTP and ddATP with 2,4-dinitrophenol (DNP). Incorporation of a single nucelotide
    					will occur based on homology to the hibridized DNA.
		</li>
  </ul>
  <center><img src="singlebaseextension.png" ></center><br>
	<ul class="list-group">
    <li class="list-group-item">
				<strong>Fluorescence Labeling</strong>: Two fluorescent labeled antibodies are used. Once against biotin, witch is labeled with green fluorescence (Cy3), and a second one against DNP labeled with
      					red fluorescence (Cy5). The use of secondary antibodies in conjunction with the fluorescently labeled ones, allows to increment the fluorescent intenisty of the beads. Unhybridized antibodies are washed away,
      					and the beadchip is coated, to protect the incorporated fluorescence.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <br>
	<ul class="list-group">
    <li class="list-group-item">
				<strong>Scan</strong>: All arrays are scanned with a HiScan instrument, resulting in IDATs files that contain the intensities values of fluorescence of each bead present in the array.
	  </li>
  </ul>
